{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01YKMSUaFHqsj24mQL9aUqV6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01X6xHEXaHZynpbiNaSdDcuk","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-parallel-execution.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":871,"cache_read_input_tokens":39664,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":871,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":68,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01T8UdeYWzSFyXWGbZbNGtaf","session_id":"9c9fe147-c536-4d36-9f64-8249f0c68839","uuid":"68d0bf16-5de6-4208-a93a-f31018050803"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01X6xHEXaHZynpbiNaSdDcuk","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tstepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]\n3\tlastStep: 8\n4\tstatus: 'complete'\n5\tcompletedAt: '2026-04-03'\n6\tinputDocuments:\n7\t  - prd.md (parallel execution PRD, 30 FRs, 13 NFRs)\n8\t  - ux-design-parallel-execution.md (multi-lane TUI UX spec)\n9\t  - architecture-multi-framework.md (workflow engine architecture, brownfield)\n10\tworkflowType: 'architecture'\n11\tproject_name: 'codeharness'\n12\tuser_name: 'BMad'\n13\tdate: '2026-04-03'\n14\t---\n15\t\n16\t# Architecture Decision Document — Parallel Execution\n17\t\n18\t_Extends architecture-multi-framework.md. All prior decisions (driver interface, output contracts, model resolution, TUI components) remain valid._\n19\t\n20\t## Project Context Analysis\n21\t\n22\t### Requirements Overview\n23\t\n24\t**Functional Requirements:**\n25\t30 FRs across 7 capability areas. Core is parallel epic execution via git worktrees (FR6-FR11), merge + validation (FR12-FR17), engine-handled null tasks (FR18-FR21), hierarchical flow model (FR1-FR5), per-epic scope (FR22-FR24), verify flag optimization (FR25-FR26), and multi-lane TUI (FR27-FR30).\n26\t\n27\t**Non-Functional Requirements:**\n28\t13 NFRs. Worktree creation <10s, multi-lane TUI at 15 FPS with 4 lanes, telemetry writes <10ms, merge <30s (non-conflicting), crash isolation between lanes, no orphaned worktrees, backward compatibility at max_parallel=1.\n29\t\n30\t**UX Requirements:**\n31\tMulti-lane TUI with side-by-side lanes (>=120 cols), stacked (80-119), single (<80). Merge status as first-class display element. Lane lifecycle events visible. Telemetry invisible by default. New Ink components: LaneContainer, Lane, CollapsedLanes, SummaryBar, MergeStatus.\n32\t\n33\t**Scale & Complexity:**\n34\t\n35\t- Primary domain: Node.js CLI with multi-process orchestration and git worktree management\n36\t- Complexity level: High — concurrent process management, git branch lifecycle, merge conflict resolution via LLM, hierarchical state machines\n37\t- Estimated new components: ~12 (worktree manager, lane pool, merge agent, hierarchical flow parser, epic completion detector, telemetry writer, 6 new Ink components)\n38\t\n39\t### Technical Constraints & Dependencies\n40\t\n41\t- **Git worktrees** — `git worktree add/remove/list`. Requires git >= 2.15. Each worktree is a separate working directory on a separate branch. Git operations must be atomic per worktree — no concurrent git commands on the same worktree.\n42\t- **Process isolation** — Each lane runs its own workflow engine instance (or async task). Lanes share the sprint-state.json on main only at merge boundaries.\n43\t- **Existing workflow engine** — Currently single-threaded, sequential. Must be refactored to support concurrent instances operating on different working directories.\n44\t- **Ink TUI** — Single React render tree. Multi-lane rendering is layout, not multi-instance. All lanes feed into the same Ink render loop.\n45\t- **State file** — sprint-state.json lives on main branch. Worktree-local state tracks per-epic progress. Merge reconciles worktree state back into main state.\n46\t\n47\t### Cross-Cutting Concerns\n48\t\n49\t1. **Concurrent git operations** — Two worktrees can `git commit` simultaneously (different branches), but `git merge` must be serialized (modifies main).\n50\t2. **State synchronization** — Sprint-state.json on main is the source of truth. Worktree-local state files track epic progress. Merge merges both code and state.\n51\t3. **Resource contention** — Multiple agent dispatches consume API rate limits from the same account. Lane pool must respect global rate limits.\n52\t4. **Error blast radius** — A crash in one lane must not corrupt another lane's worktree or state.\n53\t\n54\t## Starter Template Evaluation\n55\t\n56\t### Selected Starter: Existing codebase\n57\t\n58\t**Rationale:** Brownfield. Extends the workflow engine, adds git and multi-lane orchestration modules.\n59\t\n60\t**New modules to add:**\n61\t\n62\t```\n63\tsrc/lib/\n64\t├── worktree-manager.ts       # NEW — git worktree create/merge/cleanup lifecycle\n65\t├── lane-pool.ts              # NEW — manages concurrent lanes, scheduling\n66\t├── merge-agent.ts            # NEW — dispatches dev agent for conflict resolution\n67\t├── telemetry-writer.ts       # NEW — NDJSON append for per-story telemetry\n68\t├── hierarchical-flow.ts      # NEW — parses story_flow/epic_flow/execution from YAML\n69\t├── epic-completion.ts        # NEW — detects all-stories-done, triggers epic_flow\n70\t\n71\tsrc/lib/ink-lane.tsx          # NEW — Lane component (per-epic workflow view)\n72\tsrc/lib/ink-lane-container.tsx # NEW — LaneContainer (side-by-side layout)\n73\tsrc/lib/ink-summary-bar.tsx   # NEW — SummaryBar (done/merging/pending)\n74\tsrc/lib/ink-merge-status.tsx  # NEW — MergeStatus (conflict resolution display)\n75\tsrc/lib/ink-collapsed-lanes.tsx # NEW — CollapsedLanes (one-line summaries)\n76\t\n77\tsrc/schemas/\n78\t├── workflow.schema.json      # MODIFY — add execution, story_flow, epic_flow sections\n79\t├── telemetry.schema.json     # NEW — NDJSON entry schema\n80\t```\n81\t\n82\t## Core Architectural Decisions\n83\t\n84\t### Decision 1: Worktree Lifecycle Model\n85\t\n86\t**Decision:** Each parallel epic gets its own git worktree on a dedicated branch. The worktree manager handles the full lifecycle: create → execute → merge → validate → cleanup.\n87\t\n88\t**Worktree creation:**\n89\t```bash\n90\tgit branch codeharness/epic-{N}-{slug} main\n91\tgit worktree add /tmp/codeharness-wt-epic-{N} codeharness/epic-{N}-{slug}\n92\t```\n93\t\n94\t**Branch naming:** `codeharness/` prefix prevents collision with user branches (NFR12).\n95\t\n96\t**Worktree location:** `/tmp/codeharness-wt-epic-{N}` — temporary, cleaned up after merge. User-visible in TUI and `codeharness status`.\n97\t\n98\t**Merge flow (serialized — only one merge at a time):**\n99\t```\n100\t1. git checkout main\n101\t2. git merge codeharness/epic-{N}-{slug}\n102\t3. If conflict → dispatch merge agent\n103\t4. If resolved → run test suite\n104\t5. If tests pass → git worktree remove → git branch -d\n105\t6. If tests fail → revert merge, retry agent (up to 3 attempts), escalate\n106\t```\n107\t\n108\t**Rationale:** Git worktrees are the lightest isolation primitive — no clone overhead, shared object store. The `/tmp` location makes cleanup obvious. Branch prefix prevents accidental collision.\n109\t\n110\t### Decision 2: Lane Pool & Scheduling\n111\t\n112\t**Decision:** The engine maintains a fixed-size lane pool. Each lane is an async task (not a separate process) that runs a workflow engine instance against a worktree directory.\n113\t\n114\t**Pool structure:**\n115\t```typescript\n116\tinterface LanePool {\n117\t  maxLanes: number;           // from execution.max_parallel\n118\t  activeLanes: Map<string, Lane>;  // epicId → Lane\n119\t  pendingEpics: string[];     // ordered queue of epics to schedule\n120\t  mergeQueue: string[];       // epics waiting to merge (serialized)\n121\t}\n122\t\n123\tinterface Lane {\n124\t  epicId: string;\n125\t  worktreePath: string;\n126\t  branch: string;\n127\t  engineInstance: Promise<EngineResult>;  // async workflow execution\n128\t  status: 'executing' | 'merging' | 'validating' | 'done' | 'failed';\n129\t}\n130\t```\n131\t\n132\t**Scheduling:** When a lane frees up, the pool picks the next epic from `pendingEpics` that has no dependency on any `activeLane` epic. For MVP, dependency is determined by epic ordering — epic N can only run if no epic < N is still active (except completed ones). Post-MVP: explicit DAG from epic declarations.\n133\t\n134\t**Concurrency model:** `Promise.race()` on active lanes. When any lane completes, its result is processed (merge queued), and next epic scheduled.\n135\t\n136\t```typescript\n137\twhile (pendingEpics.length > 0 || activeLanes.size > 0) {\n138\t  // Fill lanes up to max\n139\t  while (activeLanes.size < maxLanes && hasReadyEpic()) {\n140\t    const epic = nextReadyEpic();\n141\t    const lane = await createLane(epic);\n142\t    activeLanes.set(epic.id, lane);\n143\t  }\n144\t  // Wait for any lane to complete\n145\t  const completed = await Promise.race(\n146\t    [...activeLanes.values()].map(l => l.engineInstance)\n147\t  );\n148\t  // Process completion: queue merge, free lane\n149\t  await processLaneCompletion(completed);\n150\t}\n151\t```\n152\t\n153\t**Rationale:** Async tasks (not processes) share the Node.js event loop — simpler than multi-process, and the engine already uses `async/await` throughout. `Promise.race` gives natural lane completion handling.\n154\t\n155\t### Decision 3: Merge Serialization & Agent\n156\t\n157\t**Decision:** Merges are serialized — only one `git merge` into main at a time. Conflicts dispatch a merge agent (dev agent with conflict context). Cross-worktree test validation runs after every merge.\n158\t\n159\t**Merge serialization:**\n160\t```typescript\n161\tconst mergeMutex = new Mutex();\n162\t\n163\tasync function mergeEpic(epic: Lane): Promise<MergeResult> {\n164\t  const release = await mergeMutex.acquire();\n165\t  try {\n166\t    const result = await gitMerge(epic.branch);\n167\t    if (result.conflicts.length > 0) {\n168\t      return await resolveMergeConflicts(epic, result.conflicts);\n169\t    }\n170\t    await runTestSuite();\n171\t    await cleanupWorktree(epic);\n172\t    return { success: true };\n173\t  } finally {\n174\t    release();\n175\t  }\n176\t}\n177\t```\n178\t\n179\t**Merge agent context:**\n180\t```typescript\n181\tconst mergePrompt = `\n182\tMerge conflict in ${file}:\n183\t<<<<<<< main\n184\t${mainContent}\n185\t=======\n186\t${branchContent}\n187\t>>>>>>> ${branchName}\n188\t\n189\tContext:\n190\t- Main branch: ${mainEpicDescription}\n191\t- Feature branch: ${branchEpicDescription}\n192\t- Both changes are from: ${whatBothEpicsWereBuilding}\n193\t\n194\tResolve the conflict preserving both changes. Both are correct additions.\n195\t`;\n196\t```\n197\t\n198\t**Retry policy:** 3 attempts with merge agent. If all fail, escalate to user — preserve worktree and branch for manual resolution.\n199\t\n200\t**Rationale:** Serialized merges prevent race conditions on main. The merge agent gets full semantic context, not just diff markers. 3 attempts is generous — most conflicts are additive (different functions in same file).\n201\t\n202\t### Decision 4: Hierarchical Flow Model\n203\t\n204\t**Decision:** Workflow YAML gains three sections: `execution` (sprint-level config), `story_flow` (per-story pipeline), `epic_flow` (per-epic completion tasks). The existing flat `flow:` is syntactic sugar for `story_flow:` with `execution: { max_parallel: 1 }`.\n205\t\n206\t**Schema:**\n207\t```yaml\n208\texecution:\n209\t  max_parallel: 2\n210\t  isolation: worktree\n211\t  merge_strategy: rebase       # or merge-commit\n212\t  epic_strategy: parallel      # or sequential\n213\t  story_strategy: sequential   # or parallel (post-MVP)\n214\t\n215\ttasks:\n216\t  implement: { agent: dev, scope: per-story }\n217\t  verify: { agent: evaluator, scope: per-run }\n218\t  retry: { agent: dev, scope: per-story }\n219\t  telemetry: { agent: null, scope: per-story }\n220\t  retro: { agent: analyst, scope: per-epic }\n221\t\n222\tstory_flow:\n223\t  - implement\n224\t  - verify\n225\t  - loop:\n226\t      - retry\n227\t      - verify\n228\t  - telemetry\n229\t\n230\tepic_flow:\n231\t  - retro\n232\t  - merge       # built-in\n233\t  - validate    # built-in\n234\t```\n235\t\n236\t**Backward compatibility:** If only `flow:` is present (no `story_flow`/`epic_flow`/`execution`), the engine treats it as `story_flow: <flow>` with `execution: { max_parallel: 1, epic_strategy: sequential }`. Zero behavior change for existing workflows.\n237\t\n238\t**Built-in tasks:** `merge` and `validate` are engine-handled (like `agent: null`). They don't appear in `tasks:` — the engine recognizes them as built-in epic_flow steps.\n239\t\n240\t**Rationale:** Three-level hierarchy maps naturally to sprint → epic → story. Backward compatibility means existing workflows work unchanged. Built-in merge/validate avoids forcing users to define agent configs for git operations.\n241\t\n242\t### Decision 5: Engine-Handled Null Tasks\n243\t\n244\t**Decision:** When a task has `agent: null`, the engine executes it directly without dispatching to any driver. The engine checks the task name and calls the corresponding handler.\n245\t\n246\t**Handler registry:**\n247\t```typescript\n248\tconst nullTaskHandlers: Record<string, NullTaskHandler> = {\n249\t  telemetry: writeTelemetryEntry,\n250\t  merge: mergeWorktreeToMain,\n251\t  validate: runCrossWorktreeTests,\n252\t};\n253\t\n254\tinterface NullTaskHandler {\n255\t  (context: TaskContext): Promise<TaskResult>;\n256\t}\n257\t```\n258\t\n259\t**Telemetry handler:**\n260\t```typescript\n261\tasync function writeTelemetryEntry(ctx: TaskContext): Promise<TaskResult> {\n262\t  const entry: TelemetryEntry = {\n263\t    version: 1,\n264\t    timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),\n265\t    storyKey: ctx.storyKey,\n266\t    epicId: ctx.epicId,\n267\t    duration_ms: ctx.elapsedMs,\n268\t    cost_usd: ctx.accumulatedCost,\n269\t    attempts: ctx.retryCount,\n270\t    acResults: ctx.lastVerdict?.acResults ?? null,\n271\t    filesChanged: ctx.outputContract?.changedFiles ?? [],\n272\t    testResults: ctx.outputContract?.testResults ?? null,\n273\t    errors: ctx.errors,\n274\t  };\n275\t  await appendNdjson('.codeharness/telemetry.jsonl', entry);\n276\t  return { success: true, output: 'telemetry written' };\n277\t}\n278\t```\n279\t\n280\t**Rationale:** Null tasks are pure data operations — no LLM needed. The handler registry is extensible. New built-in tasks just add a handler function.\n281\t\n282\t### Decision 6: Epic Completion Detection\n283\t\n284\t**Decision:** The engine tracks per-epic story counts. When all stories in an epic reach `done`, the engine triggers `epic_flow` tasks in sequence.\n285\t\n286\t**Detection logic:**\n287\t```typescript\n288\tfunction checkEpicCompletion(state: SprintState, epicId: string): boolean {\n289\t  const epicStories = getStoriesForEpic(state, epicId);\n290\t  return epicStories.every(s => s.status === 'done');\n291\t}\n292\t```\n293\t\n294\t**Epic state transitions:**\n295\t- `backlog` → `in-progress`: when lane is created for this epic\n296\t- `in-progress` → `completing`: when all stories done, epic_flow starts\n297\t- `completing` → `merging`: epic_flow reaches merge step\n298\t- `merging` → `validating`: merge succeeded, running tests\n299\t- `validating` → `done`: tests passed, worktree cleaned\n300\t- `validating` → `failed`: tests failed after 3 merge agent attempts\n301\t\n302\t**Rationale:** Epic completion is deterministic — just count done stories. The multi-step completion state (completing → merging → validating → done) gives the TUI and status command precise information about where the epic is in its lifecycle.\n303\t\n304\t### Decision 7: Verify Flag Propagation\n305\t\n306\t**Decision:** The workflow engine sets `tests_passed` and `coverage_met` from the dev task's output contract, before dispatching the verify task.\n307\t\n308\t**Implementation:**\n309\t```typescript\n310\t// After implement task completes:\n311\tif (taskName === 'implement' && outputContract?.testResults) {\n312\t  const { passed, failed, coverage } = outputContract.testResults;\n313\t  if (failed === 0) await setState('tests_passed', true);\n314\t  if (coverage >= state.coverage.target) await setState('coverage_met', true);\n315\t}\n316\t```\n317\t\n318\t**Coverage deduplication:** The verify task receives test results via output contract. The evaluator checks the contract's `testResults` field instead of re-running coverage. If `testResults.coverage >= target`, coverage is already met — no re-run.\n319\t\n320\t**Rationale:** The engine has all the data it needs from the output contract. Setting flags in the engine is deterministic and reliable — no dependency on the evaluator's ability to set flags in a subagent context.\n321\t\n322\t### Decision 8: Multi-Lane TUI Architecture\n323\t\n324\t**Decision:** The Ink render tree gains a `LaneContainer` component that manages lane layout. Each lane is a `Lane` component wrapping existing `WorkflowGraph` + `StoryProgress`. The renderer receives events from all active lanes and routes them by lane ID.\n325\t\n326\t**Event routing:**\n327\t```typescript\n328\tinterface LaneEvent {\n329\t  laneId: string;        // epic ID\n330\t  event: StreamEvent;    // from driver\n331\t}\n332\t\n333\t// Renderer maintains per-lane state\n334\tconst laneStates: Map<string, LaneState> = new Map();\n335\t\n336\tfunction updateLane(laneEvent: LaneEvent) {\n337\t  const state = laneStates.get(laneEvent.laneId);\n338\t  // Update lane-specific state (story, phase, cost, tools)\n339\t  // Only the most recently active lane shows in activity section\n340\t}\n341\t```\n342\t\n343\t**Layout decision (from UX spec):**\n344\t- >=120 cols: side-by-side columns\n345\t- 80-119 cols: stacked vertically (compact)\n346\t- <80 cols: single active lane, others collapsed\n347\t\n348\t**Component tree:**\n349\t```\n350\t<App>\n351\t  <Header />                     # Extended: lane count\n352\t  <Separator />\n353\t  <LaneContainer width={cols}>   # NEW: manages layout mode\n354\t    <Lane epicId=\"10\" />         # NEW: per-epic view\n355\t    <Lane epicId=\"14\" />\n356\t    <CollapsedLanes lanes={3+} /> # NEW: overflow\n357\t  </LaneContainer>\n358\t  <Separator />\n359\t  <SummaryBar />                 # NEW: done/merging/pending\n360\t  <MergeStatus />                # NEW: active merge progress\n361\t  <Separator />\n362\t  <ActivityDisplay laneId={activeLane} />  # Existing: filtered by lane\n363\t</App>\n364\t```\n365\t\n366\t**Rationale:** Single Ink render tree with lane-routed state. No multiple Ink instances — that would break terminal rendering. The `LaneContainer` handles responsive layout based on terminal width.\n367\t\n368\t## Implementation Patterns & Consistency Rules\n369\t\n370\t### Worktree Operations Pattern\n371\t\n372\t**All git operations MUST:**\n373\t- Use `child_process.execSync` for atomic git commands (create branch, add worktree)\n374\t- Use `child_process.exec` with timeout for potentially slow operations (merge, test suite)\n375\t- Capture stderr for error reporting\n376\t- Clean up on failure (remove partially created worktrees)\n377\t\n378\t### Lane Isolation Pattern\n379\t\n380\t**Each lane MUST:**\n381\t- Set `cwd` to its worktree path for all agent dispatches\n382\t- Write worktree-local state to `{worktreePath}/.codeharness/lane-state.json`\n383\t- Never read or write main branch's sprint-state.json during execution\n384\t- Report results back to the lane pool via the lane's `Promise<EngineResult>`\n385\t\n386\t### Merge Safety Pattern\n387\t\n388\t**Merge operations MUST:**\n389\t- Acquire the merge mutex before any git operation on main\n390\t- Run `git status` before merge to verify main is clean\n391\t- Run the full test suite after merge (not just affected tests)\n392\t- On test failure: revert merge (`git reset --hard HEAD~1`), retry with agent context\n393\t- On 3 failures: preserve worktree, log escalation, continue with other lanes\n394\t\n395\t### Telemetry Write Pattern\n396\t\n397\t**Telemetry entries MUST:**\n398\t- Use append-only NDJSON (one `JSON.stringify` + `\\n` per entry)\n399\t- Include `version: 1` field for forward compatibility\n400\t- Write atomically — buffer the line, write with `appendFileSync`\n401\t- Never read from telemetry.jsonl during the run (write-only during execution)\n402\t\n403\t## Project Structure & Boundaries\n404\t\n405\t### New Files\n406\t\n407\t```\n408\tsrc/lib/\n409\t├── worktree-manager.ts       # Git worktree lifecycle (create/merge/cleanup)\n410\t├── lane-pool.ts              # Lane scheduling, Promise.race loop\n411\t├── merge-agent.ts            # Conflict resolution dispatch\n412\t├── telemetry-writer.ts       # NDJSON append\n413\t├── hierarchical-flow.ts      # Parse execution/story_flow/epic_flow\n414\t├── epic-completion.ts        # All-stories-done detection\n415\t├── ink-lane.tsx              # Lane component\n416\t├── ink-lane-container.tsx    # Layout manager (side-by-side/stacked/single)\n417\t├── ink-summary-bar.tsx       # Done/merging/pending bar\n418\t├── ink-merge-status.tsx      # Merge progress display\n419\t├── ink-collapsed-lanes.tsx   # One-line lane summaries\n420\t\n421\tsrc/schemas/\n422\t├── workflow.schema.json      # MODIFY: execution, story_flow, epic_flow\n423\t├── telemetry.schema.json     # NEW: NDJSON entry schema\n424\t\n425\ttest/\n426\t├── unit/\n427\t│   ├── worktree-manager.test.ts\n428\t│   ├── lane-pool.test.ts\n429\t│   ├── merge-agent.test.ts\n430\t│   ├── telemetry-writer.test.ts\n431\t│   ├── hierarchical-flow.test.ts\n432\t│   ├── epic-completion.test.ts\n433\t│   └── ink-lane-container.test.tsx\n434\t```\n435\t\n436\t### Modified Files\n437\t\n438\t```\n439\tsrc/lib/workflow-engine.ts    # Integrate lane pool, epic_flow, null tasks\n440\tsrc/lib/workflow-parser.ts    # Parse hierarchical flow YAML\n441\tsrc/lib/ink-app.tsx           # Add LaneContainer to render tree\n442\tsrc/lib/ink-renderer.tsx      # Lane event routing, multi-lane state\n443\tsrc/lib/ink-components.tsx    # Header extension (lane count)\n444\tsrc/commands/run.ts           # Parallel execution orchestration\n445\tsrc/commands/status.ts        # Parallel run status display\n446\tsrc/schemas/workflow.schema.json  # Execution, story_flow, epic_flow\n447\t```\n448\t\n449\t### Architectural Boundaries\n450\t\n451\t**Worktree Manager Boundary:**\n452\t- ONLY knows git operations. Does NOT know about agents, stories, or TUI.\n453\t- Interface: `createWorktree(epicId) → path`, `mergeWorktree(epicId) → MergeResult`, `cleanupWorktree(epicId)`\n454\t\n455\t**Lane Pool Boundary:**\n456\t- Manages lane lifecycle and scheduling. Does NOT execute stories directly.\n457\t- Delegates to workflow engine instances per lane.\n458\t- Interface: `startPool(epics, maxParallel) → AsyncIterable<LaneEvent>`\n459\t\n460\t**Merge Agent Boundary:**\n461\t- Wraps the dev agent with merge-specific context. Does NOT know about worktrees or lanes.\n462\t- Interface: `resolveConflict(conflicts, context) → Promise<boolean>`\n463\t\n464\t**TUI Boundary:**\n465\t- Receives `LaneEvent` objects. Does NOT manage lanes or worktrees.\n466\t- Layout logic is purely presentational — responds to terminal width.\n467\t\n468\t### FR to Structure Mapping\n469\t\n470\t| FR Capability Area | Files |\n471\t|-------------------|-------|\n472\t| Hierarchical Flow (FR1-FR5) | `hierarchical-flow.ts`, `workflow-parser.ts`, `workflow.schema.json` |\n473\t| Parallel Execution (FR6-FR11) | `worktree-manager.ts`, `lane-pool.ts`, `run.ts` |\n474\t| Merge & Validation (FR12-FR17) | `worktree-manager.ts`, `merge-agent.ts` |\n475\t| Engine-Handled Tasks (FR18-FR21) | `workflow-engine.ts`, `telemetry-writer.ts` |\n476\t| Per-Epic Scope (FR22-FR24) | `epic-completion.ts`, `workflow-engine.ts` |\n477\t| Verify Flags (FR25-FR26) | `workflow-engine.ts` |\n478\t| Multi-Lane TUI (FR27-FR30) | `ink-lane*.tsx`, `ink-summary-bar.tsx`, `ink-merge-status.tsx` |\n479\t\n480\t### Data Flow\n481\t\n482\t```\n483\tWorkflow YAML → hierarchical-flow parser → execution config + story_flow + epic_flow\n484\t    ↓\n485\tlane-pool → schedule epics (respecting max_parallel + dependencies)\n486\t    ↓\n487\tworktree-manager → create worktree per epic\n488\t    ↓\n489\tworkflow-engine (per lane) → execute story_flow for each story in epic\n490\t    ↓\n491\t    ├→ LaneEvent stream → ink-renderer → multi-lane TUI\n492\t    ├→ telemetry-writer → .codeharness/telemetry.jsonl (per story)\n493\t    └→ epic-completion detector → triggers epic_flow\n494\t         ↓\n495\t         ├→ retro task (agent: analyst with telemetry data)\n496\t         ├→ merge (worktree-manager → git merge, serialized)\n497\t         │    ↓ on conflict → merge-agent → resolve → retry merge\n498\t         ├→ validate (run test suite on merged main)\n499\t         └→ cleanup (worktree-manager → remove worktree + branch)\n500\t```\n501\t\n502\t## Architecture Validation Results\n503\t\n504\t### Requirements Coverage\n505\t\n506\t**Functional Requirements:** 30/30 FRs architecturally supported ✓\n507\t\n508\t**Non-Functional Requirements:** 13/13 NFRs architecturally supported ✓\n509\t- NFR1 (worktree <10s): `git worktree add` is fast (shared object store)\n510\t- NFR2 (TUI 15 FPS): single Ink instance, lane state routing only\n511\t- NFR6 (crash isolation): Promise-based lanes, independent worktrees\n512\t- NFR8 (state consistency): worktree-local state, merge-time reconciliation\n513\t- NFR10 (backward compat): flat `flow:` → `story_flow` with `max_parallel: 1`\n514\t\n515\t### Architecture Readiness Assessment\n516\t\n517\t**Overall Status:** READY FOR IMPLEMENTATION\n518\t**Confidence Level:** High\n519\t\n520\t**Key Strengths:**\n521\t- Async lane pool with `Promise.race` — natural concurrent scheduling without multi-process complexity\n522\t- Git worktrees provide free isolation with zero clone overhead\n523\t- Serialized merges eliminate race conditions on main\n524\t- Backward compatible — existing workflows unchanged at `max_parallel: 1`\n525\t\n526\t**First Implementation Priority:** Worktree manager + lane pool (FR6-FR9), then hierarchical flow parser (FR1-FR2), then wire into run command.\n527\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01T8UdeYWzSFyXWGbZbNGtaf","session_id":"9c9fe147-c536-4d36-9f64-8249f0c68839","uuid":"96074dcf-46e9-41f8-88fd-11397635c230","timestamp":"2026-04-03T16:37:30.413Z"}
